 Stoicism, Frede begins with Aristotle--who, he argues, had no notion of a free will--and ends with Augustine. Frede shows that Augustine, far from originating the idea (as is often claimed), derived most of his thinking about it from the Stoicism developed by Epictetus.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aFree will and determinismxHistory. 0aPhilosophy, Ancient. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aancient greeks.  aaristotelian philosophy.  aaristotle.  aaugustine.  achristian thinkers.  achristianity.  adivine providence.  adivine will.  adivinity.  aepictetus.  aepistemology.  afree will.  agreek philosophy.  aindividual choice.  ametaphysics.  anonfiction.  aperipatetic.  aphilosophy.  aplato.  aprovidence.  arational choice.  arational self interest.  areligion.  aself control.  aself enslavement.  aspirituality.  astoic philosophy.  astoicism.  atheory of assent.  avolition.  awill.1 aLong, A. A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052026848740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094837240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520948372423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520948372/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY